<subSubSection pageId="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1233,1945]" pageId="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1233,1258]" pageId="8">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Head a little wider than mesonotum, with posterior margin slightly concave; genal processes often present, of variable size and shape (
<figureCitation box="[550,634,1269,1294]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 27. Head, anterodorsal view. 10. Gyropsylla sp. 11. Lanthanaphalara sp. 12. Limataphalara hollisi. 13. Ctenarytaina spatulata. 14. Glycaspis brimblecombei. 15. Syncoptozus mexicanus. 16. Paracarsidara sp. 17. Synoza cornutiventris. 18. Caradocia sp. 19. Diaphorina citri. 20. Katacephala sp. 21. Tuthillia latipennis. 22 – 23. Calophya schini. 24 – 25. Mastigimas sp. 26. Acizzia uncatoides. 27. Ciriacremum sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059237/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
); genae with a prominent basal swelling below the eye (
<figureCitation box="[1260,1343,1269,1294]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 27. Head, anterodorsal view. 10. Gyropsylla sp. 11. Lanthanaphalara sp. 12. Limataphalara hollisi. 13. Ctenarytaina spatulata. 14. Glycaspis brimblecombei. 15. Syncoptozus mexicanus. 16. Paracarsidara sp. 17. Synoza cornutiventris. 18. Caradocia sp. 19. Diaphorina citri. 20. Katacephala sp. 21. Tuthillia latipennis. 22 – 23. Calophya schini. 24 – 25. Mastigimas sp. 26. Acizzia uncatoides. 27. Ciriacremum sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059237/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
, arrow). Antennae short, about as long as head width; sometimes with less than 10 segments; segment 3 always the longest; terminal setae usually much longer than segment 10. Forewing of variable shape; pterostigma present but may be very narrow; costal break present; cell cu1 large, m1 small; anal break in distance of apex of Cu1b. Meracanthus short, pointed and straight; metatibia without genual spine and 1+(2–5) apical spurs; metabasitarsus without apical spurs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1233,1945]" pageId="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,455,1488,1513]" pageId="8">Biology and damage:</emphasis>
Immatures of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tuthill" authorityYear="1959" box="[624,808,1488,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Calophyidae" genus="Calophya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schini">
<emphasis box="[624,808,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="8">Calophya schini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
induce pit galls on leaves, shoots and buds of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Schinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="molle">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8">Schinus molle</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[230,399,1524,1549]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Anacardiaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[425,511,1524,1549]" captionStart="FIGURES 71 – 76. 71" captionStartId="19.[151,264,785,808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,206,765]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,765]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 71 – 76. 71. Pit-galls of Calophya schini on Schinus molle. 72 – 73. Mastigimas cedrelae on Cedrela montana. 74. Tuthillia latipennis on Myrcianthes sp. 75 – 76. Acizzia uncatoides on Acacia sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059247/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
). High infestation produces tissue deformation due to elevated number of galls, which may result in premature defoliation and dessication of branches (
<bibRefCitation author="Pinzon" box="[952,1241,1560,1585]" pageId="8" refString="Pinzon, O. P. &amp; Gonzalez, R. H. (2002) Caracterizacion biologica, habitos, enemigos naturales y fluctuacion poblacional de Calophya schini Tuthill, en la especie forestal ornamental Schinus molle L. en Bogota. Revista Cientifica, 2002, 137 - 154." type="journal article" year="2002">Pinzón &amp; González 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
